climbs.name: Seam-and-Crack
climbs.fa: Unknown, but most likely in the early 1970s.

content.description: The thin seam at the start of this route is the 5.10c crux.
content.location: The next route on the cliff to the right of the obvious Inside Corner (5.8) fist crack.

climbs.name: Inside Corner
climbs.fa: Unknown, but most likely in the early 1970s

content.description: A short fist crack on the inside corner to the right of the Blunt Arēte (5.10d TR)
content.protection: Arrange natural TR anchors on top.
content.location: Obvious inside corner with a fist crack just to the right of the Blunt Arête

climbs.name: Hidden Crack
climbs.fa: Unknown, but likely in the early 1970s

content.protection: Build natural anchors on top after accessing from the right.
content.location: Around in the alcove to the right of The Climb-Me Flake (5.7)

climbs.name: Easy Crack Corner
climbs.fa: Unknown, but most likely in the early 1970s

content.protection: Arrange natural anchors on top if TRed. Takes good lead pro.
content.location: 6 feet to the right of Hidden Crack (5.10a)

climbs.name: The Climb-Me Flake
climbs.fa: Unknown, but most likely in the early 1970s.

content.description: Although short, this feature is so obvious and clean that it positively calls out to be climbed.
content.location: The obvious flake to the right of Seam-and-Crack (5.10c)

climbs.name: Clean Crack
climbs.fa: Unknown, but most likely in the 1970s

content.description: This crack jogs slightly to the left at the top.
content.protection: Nuts and camming devices if not TRed or soloed as a boulder problem.

climbs.name: Blunt Arete
climbs.fa: Unknown, but most likely in the 1970s

content.description: The obvious arête on the left-hand side of the cliff to the right of Clean Crack (5.9). Difficult without the right beta.
content.protection: Rig TR anchors on top using natural protection.
